It might not be possible with just CSS.

What you really need is JavaScript. Because without it you are just setting the visibility of the inner lists to `visibility: hidden` and items with visibility set to hidden are taken in consideration when generating the layout of a `div` or a page. This is the reason there is overflow in the x direction.

With just CSS you will have to set a constant width of the main list that can accommodate the inner lists.

Below is the CSS that I tried and works with fixed width. Put it in place of the CSS that you are adding. So instead of this:

    li.dropdown ul {
      overflow-y: scroll;
      height: 300px;
    }

Add this:

    li.dropdown ul {
      overflow-y: scroll;
      overflow-x: hidden;
      height: 300px;
      width: 450px;
    }
    
    li {
       width: 100px;
    }

